Yeeeeeah... you'd have to go back a few thousands years to find that.  And lets not forget, that just because it's old to you doesn't mean it's not new to someone else.  Oh and why is it okay for you and I to watch the same movie over and over and over and over again if we want to, but don't hollywood dare remake a movie that's clearly inspired by something else. text: The way I always picture a sequel in my head, although it's a little cliché, is that when alien connected telepathically with the President it was too much information all at once and he only saw glimpses of the last part of the connection. Over time, it slowly started unravelling and the consciousness of the alien was imprinted in his mind, driving him partly mad with the information, and weakening his constitution to the point where he was mentally being taken over by the alien consciousness. Secretly, it was keeping the President under control subconsciously. It waited until it had enough control to make him fulfill tasks, and made him send a message out to the main alien fleet once humans had reversed engineered the tech to use their power source, and their communication technology. During/After, he was discovered. The President, in a moment of lucidity, agreed he needed to be kept locked away or in solitary, but no one could tell if the alien was still in control or not and just agreeing to save itself, if the he was still under control, or if the alien was also slowly being influenced by the human memories/emotions/etc and falling back to more even ground mentally with the President/human, since he was openly telling them about the information that was unravelling in his mind as he was going mad.   Another aspect being that their entire civilization only became "like locusts" because they were driven off by another race that behaved the same way. With their civilization's home destroyed, they obsessed over it. The militarization of their entire race started happening, vowing that it would never be a victim again, but the victors. They started engineering themselves biologically for war and occupation, intially not destroying worlds but forcefully occupying them. Over time, they cared less and less about saving life from extinction as they occupied and saw it as a hindrance on their goals. The military-like leaders put in a type of emotional block while growing new soldiers so they would not disobey orders and do what needed to be done. They started going from one system to another just like those who drove them from their own world. The alien's partial consciousness in the ex-President's mind, being exposed to the human emotions confused and started affectimg it, breaking down some of the emotional blocking it had, making it go a bit insane as well trying to understand and process it. With them both kinda losing it, they started understanding one better, having lucid mental conversations of a sort for short periods of time.  I had many more ideas of how to go about it, but I'll leave it at that. Thanks for reading, anyone who took the time. :) Peace.

text: I was also disappointed to see no Will Smith, but really, if you think about it, he's not that good of an actor in certain kinds of movies, and this is one of them. He doesn't pull off serious very well all the time (sometimes, but not all the time). His goofy smile is nearly impossible to hide when it's time to be deadly serious, so it betrays the required emotions on the screen. This movie might end up being better without him.  It's either (1) his schedule couldn't accommodate ID:R, (2) Fox didn't want to pony up $20+ million, or (3) the screenplay is so bad that Will said no to $20+ million. Let's hope it ain't numero 3.

text: For whatever reason (his reasons probably), Will Smith is not in this and that is going to hurt this movie. When Independence Day came out in 1996, the super, overblown scifi blockbuster was NOT the norm, so the (spectacular) special effects could sell the movie alone. Having a fun, solid cast was just the icing on the cake. Now that every other flick coming out has giant aliens/spaceships/robots/explosions/graphic cg warfare in it, the only thing that will make a film like this stand out is a fun, solid cast.Will Smith plus Jeff Goldblum has my ticket sold. Just Jeff Goldblum (whom I love, don't get me wrong)... has me waiting to read the tomatometer.    Regarding special effects and theatrical action... what was new and exciting in '96 is repetitive and mundane today. But good characters and story never get old. This trailer didn't sell me on the characters and story.

Now in 2016 this seems like just another movie that happened to have the original cast and title, but not much else to make it re capture the feel of the original. Its just wrong timing even if it turns out to be a good movie by itself, its just not original anymore. Hollywood like to dig up old projects and make them worse, this has that feeling to it. They should have just leave it for what it was at the time when it was created. Make a special Blue Ray edition or something but don't make another movie.

Nothing new or original in this trailer though, so it might only be worth watching if you haven't seen the first  according to cinemablend If you watched the debut trailer for Independence Day: Resurgence that dropped earlier today, you probably noticed an interesting lack of Will Smith's Steven Hiller.  In reality this is because the actor wound up being too expensive for the production, but given that the character's son is one of the main heroes of the movie, many have wondered exactly what happened to the hero. text: So, our huge mothership got hacked by one lousy scout craft, and then all our shields went down and all our absurdly low flying 'space' ships in the atmosphere got blowed up by conventional air fighters. What to do ? Send an even bigger-er mothership to smash those puny humans, hopefully with some better antivirus software... That is some Decepticon level logic there, I mean, space is the ultimate high ground, and the humans only have so many ships, and almost nothing that can actually leave orbit. Why not just send a huge swarm of smaller craft and just net some space rocks, and drop some extinction-sized meteors on Earth, see if any human scum remain, then drop a ton more meteors, just to be sure ? Its not like they were being careful to not kill everyone last time. Oh wait, we need to win this somehow ? Well, nevermind then, just send another easily hackable, completely non-maneuverable mothership back into the Earth's atmosphere, low enough for Earth based fighters to attack it, what's the worst that could happen ?

text: For a lot of people the 20-years-after-secuels are kind of pointless, but I personally think this movie has a lot of sense in the making, why? Most of the authors of aliens books say that if someday we are visited by an extraterrestrial race, there are two chances; 1.- They come to help us in our development as race and society teaching us the use of technology for a better life quality; 2.- They're hostiles, here are two more possibilities, a) They won and take over the planet, b) They lose but they come back with renforcements and try again, so considering all of this, is more than logic that they would come back as per the 20 years after maybe for them there wasn't 20 years, remember all the Interstellar stuff about time in space, they're probably getting back right after they knew they were defeated:  Other points that worth to be mentioned:  - President Whitmore dreaming about 'they're coming back'. Has a lot of sense, why? Remember one of them get into his brain, and intencionally (or not) they created a connection with a human, so it's logic Mr. President can see or feel things, specially because aliens use Telekinesis to communicate each other.  - Using their technology, David Levinson says that is to strengthen our planet, maybe that wasn't the first intention but it makes sense, how often can you make experiments out of a completely new technology.  - Different space ships and plan, of course if their original plan didn't work they must use another tactics and better gear.

text: A 150 million dollar introduction to a new series that will try to fill the hole stargate left.... possibly... lets hope so....   The movie went alright until the aliens show up with the "even bigger" ship this time. That ship was so big if it landed on earth for real it would've destroyed the planet, even passing earth would've made huge damage. and yet there it was parking accross the atlantic ocean somehow affecting china's cities.   The end was the worst, I think the script writers realised in what huge sh-t the huumans were in and with no plausible escape they invented the hive queen thing... why did the alien fighters fell from the sky when the queen died is beyond me but if it wasn't done even without a queen the aliens would've won.... They almost did it right with the human forces fighting the aliens inside the huge ship in that alien environment but that scene was terribly short and terribly misused.  The sfx or cgi was awesome, pure eye candy as most of modern films,  So if you like that sort of stuff you'l be pleased.  The disappointment comes from the script point of view.

text: Perhaps if you are tired or drunk the movie would get a solid 7/10. Otherwise, I would give it a 5/10 or perhaps a 6/10.. and that is out of generosity.  Also, what is up with the larger alien ships and bigger weapons? Was that supposed to be more scary and dangerous to give the movie more excitement? Well, I do not think it really did the movie justice to be fair. It is really missing the charm like in the first movie, and they did not need to have such big weapons and alien ships to make that movie as good as it is. And what is up with all the patriotism and American flags all over the place? Especially with the exclamations that "We are going to save the world becuase we are Americans"? I thought the whole world of nations came together to fight against the alien invasion, not just America.  **Warning, Spoiler alert**: The Queen could not strictly shoot/hit a school bus driving in a (fairly) straight line, but can without a problem knock out and shoot out a bunch of flying attack planes.. Cmon, really?  Nah, it is not a great movie or anything along those lines... but it is a time-killer, that is for certain.

text: I'll admit that they could've done way better on this movie. When it comes to sequels, they're not always that great; nothing beats an original. However, the idea of the Alien Queen was interesting. There are two main things I would've changed to the movie: No CGI aliens (Make them look realistic like back in 1996) and make the plot a little more serious. Me and some of my friends thought it was filmed for a more younger audience unlike the first movie. And the story seemed too rushed for some reason. The introduction of another extraterrestrial race is interesting, a more peaceful one than invasive, but could've gotten into way more detail about them. One thing I really liked is how they brought Dylan back from the first movie now as a grown young man taking after his father. In other words, the movie was fairly okay to watch, but like most sequels attempting to be as good as the original, they could've put a little more effort into developing it a tad better. After I came out of the theater I said to my friends "the trailer was better than the movie itself".

text: If you're woke like me then you'll be disgusted by these kinds of films with their anti-alien bigotry. We just need to be more tolerant towards extraterrestrials and their respective traditions and cultures. Ok so in this case their culture involves mining the Earth's core. So what? Who are we to say that our culture is superior to theirs? How dare we. We should be ashamed of our human privilege. These poor aliens are probably fleeing war, famine and persecution in their homeland and yet the heartless humans with their human privilege refuse to welcome them and even attack them. We're lucky enough to have a nice, safe planet to live on and these poor aliens have no such luxury. And then at the end of the film the humans even talk about wiping out the entire alien race! So all of the humans in the film are just Nazis anyway.

text: I may be the only one, but hell, I loved this movie. Sure, it's cheesy, high-budget disaster-alien-invasion film, with a lot of rather daft stuff (yes, not idiotic, stupid or dumb, but namely daft - playfully so)... Which 96' was too. But it adds more things to the lore and effects were pretty good. My only complaint is... You. Yes, you - the moviegoer and 'average critic'. You say that this movie doesn't have 'heart and soul' of the original. As a man, who watches the original fairly regularly and loves it a lot for what it is - a silly dis-alien-ster flick with pretty great effects and in my opinion - pretty superb acting (surpising, ain't it?). And while I understand complaints about both films being somewhat US-centric, they have deeper meaning and a great message - Unity is key to our survival.

text: I rewatched the original 1996 Independence Day recently and tbh I remember it being more epic the first time I watched it than the second time. This movie though was so much more action packed from start till finish, they really ramped up the effects here while the first movie only lived off the city sized flying saucer backdrop and the fleet of jets as its highlights.
